to identify the Civil War hospitals with the very essence of American democratic life, and his writing during this period includes some of his most urgent reflections on suffering, sympathy, violence, and love. Davis concludes this study with an essay on the contemporary medical writer Richard Selzer, who develops the implications of Whitman's ideas into a new theory of medical narrative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory. 0aHumanities. 0aLiterature and medicinezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMedicine in literature. 0aMedicinexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aMedicinexHistory. 0aMedicinezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPoetry. 0aPoets, AmericanxBiographyx19th century. 0aPoets, AmericanxBiographyy19th century. 0aPoets, Americany19th centuryvBiography. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  a19th century medicine.  aamerican civil war.  aautobiography.  abiographical account.  achallenging texts.  acompelling biography.  acontemporary medicine.  aconvalescence.  acorrespondence.  acultural icon.  afamous american authors.  agay writers.  ainnovative study.  ajournalistic works.  algbt author.  alit crit.  aliterary figure.  aliterary studies.  amale nurse.  amedical narrative.  amemoir.  aoscar wilde.  apoint of convergence.  asocially significant authors.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020760840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520918641?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918641423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918641/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-al